# Exercise 2: Estimation of an univariate model
# ---------------------------------------------------------

# Assuming that SLR. 1-4 hold then we use in ( R-markdown)

$$
gdp_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot surname_i + u_i
$$

# changes this from epsilon to ui which matches the code given in lecture 


# Part 2: using the LM to estimate the coefficients in the model 
# so GDP is Y (dependent) and then surname is X (independent)
model <- lm(gdp ~ surname, data = merged_df )
print(model)

# Interpretation: use in markdown 
# - $\hat \beta_0$ (intercept): The intercept of 10,077 represents the predicted GDP (in million CHF)
# when the share of the surnames Müller and Maier is 0 in a canton. Here the figure
# represents a baseline GDP level for the regression.


# - $\hat \beta_1$ : Since here the surname coefficient is measured as a proportion of the permanent population,
# an increase in the surname share by 1 percentage point (e.g from 4% to 5%) would increase predicted
# GDP by 4495 million CHF, on average. 


# Part 3
# Average surname share across cantons
avg_surname <- mean(merged_df$surname)

# Find predicted GDP with the regression coefficents
predicted_gdp <- predict(model, newdata = data.frame(surname = avg_surname))


# compute predicted GDP using the regression coefficients
predicted_avg_gdp <- as.numeric(model$coefficients[1] + 
                                  model$coefficients[2] * avg_surname)

print(predicted_avg_gdp)

# For a canton that has the average share of Müllers and Maiers then the model will predict,
# on average, a GDP of approximately 28,656 million CHF.

