# What does R^2 measure 
# R^2 measures how much of the variation in GDP across swiss cantons can be explained by a
# explanatory variable in the regression model. In our case we have 2 regression models explaining the variation in 
# GDP giving us a value for the fit of the model on the data. 


# Amount of variation in GDP explained
# In this case the model with "surname" explains about 64.3 % of the variation in GDP across the cantons,
# whereas the model with ln(immigration), has a lower R^2 value so it only explains 
# 60.5 % of the variation in the GDP. We can say that the model with the surnames
# has a higher predictive power in this sample. 

# Part 3: Discuss unbiasedness and SLR.4
# The assumption for SLR.4 (Zero Conditional Mean) has to hold so that the estimators of the coefficients on surname and ln(immigration) are unbiased. 
# This means that the explanatory variable should be uncorrelated with the error term, so the error term u_i has to have an expected value of 0 given any value of X. 
# In these models, this assumption of SLR. 4 is unlikely to hold, because many important determinants of GDP are omitted. 
# Some examples of these hidden determinants could be the industry concentration or regional geography (e.g., being in the industrial Swiss-German region). 
# Therefore these omitted factors could mistakenly be corrolated to immigration levels or the share of surnames in a canton.
# If we omit such determinants, the explanatory variables may be correlated to the error term which leads to omitted variable bias.
# Consequently, the estimated coefficients wouldnt be unbiased estimates, and we should treat them as associations rather than causal effects.




# Part 4: Relationship between unbiasedness and predictive power (R^2)
# The unbiasedness of a coefficient estimator and the predictive power of a model (measured by R^2) 
# measure different aspects of a regression model. Unbiasedness refers to whether the estimator 
# correctly estimates the true population parameter on average, which depends on assumptions such as the SLR. 4.
# Predictive power measured by R^2 indicates how weell the model explains the variation in the data but doesnt gaurantee
# unbiased estimates.



